04541nam a22006015i 9780520352520DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203525207 a10.1525/97805203525202doi  a(DE-B1597)648683  a(OCoLC)1408682493  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aNC1765b.C73 2013 7aPER0170002bisacsh04a791.43/34223/eng/202403051 aCrafton, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShadow of a Mouse :bPerformance, Belief, and World-Making in Animation /cDonald Crafton; ed. by Donald Crafton. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b21 color images, 72 black & white images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Six Cartoon Conundra -- tPart One. Animation Per for mance -- tChapter 1 Performance in and of Animation -- tChapter 2 Live and in Person: Toons! -- tPart Two. Historical Contingencies -- tChapter 3 The Acme of Variegated Entertainment -- tChapter 4 Shadow of a Mouse: Animation Performance Spaces -- tPart Three. Instrumental Animation -- tChapter 5 Infectious Laughter -- tChapter 6 Animation and Autophagy: Art that Consumes Itself -- tCoda: The Shadow of a Mouse’s Tail -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnimation variously entertains, enchants, and offends, yet there have been no convincing explanations of how these films do so. Shadow of a Mouse proposes performance as the common touchstone for understanding the principles underlying the construction, execution, and reception of cartoons. Donald Crafton’s interdisciplinary methods draw on film and theater studies, art history, aesthetics, cultural studies, and performance studies to outline a personal view of animated cinema that illuminates its systems of belief and world making. He wryly asks: Are animated characters actors and stars, just like humans? Why do their performances seem live and present, despite our knowing that they are drawings? Why is animation obsessed with distressing the body? Why were California regional artists and Stanislavsky so influential on Disney? Why are the histories of animation and popular theater performance inseparable? How was pictorial space constructed to accommodate embodied acting? Do cartoon performances stimulate positive or negative behaviors in audiences? Why is there so much extreme eating? And why are seemingly insignificant shadows vitally important? Ranging from classics like The Three Little Pigs to contemporary works by Švankmajer and Plympton, these essays will engage the reader’s imagination as much as the subject of animation performance itself.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimated filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aCartoon characters. 0aCharacters and characteristics in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture acting. 4aAnimation (see also Film Genres Animated). 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Animation (see also Film / Genres / Animated).2bisacsh1 aCrafton, Donald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026104440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035252040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520352520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520352520/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles